  "prompt": "Which one is grammatically correct: pick up someone at the airport or from the airport?",
  "response": "Both \"pick up someone at the airport\" and \"pick up someone from the airport\" are grammatically correct, but they have slightly different connotations:\n\n1. \"Pick up someone at the airport\" is more commonly used and suggests meeting someone at the airport location.\n\n2. \"Pick up someone from the airport\" implies bringing someone away from the airport to another location.\n\nIn everyday speech, most people use both interchangeably, and both are widely understood. If you want to be most precise, \"pick up someone at the airport\" is slightly more standard.",
